for some a symbol of superstition and oppression, for others a “wonder of the world.” Now a World Heritage Site, it is visited by thousands of travelers every year.In this intriguing study, Henry Kamen looks at the circumstances that brought the young Philip II to commission construction of the Escorial in 1563. He explores Philip’s motivation, the influence of his travels, the meaning of the design, and its place in Spanish culture. It represents a highly engaging narrative of the high point of Spanish imperial dominance, in which contemporary preoccupations with art, religion, and power are analyzed in the context of this remarkable building.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aArchitecture and societyzSpainzSan Lorenzo del EscorialxHistoryy16th century. 0aArt and societyzSpainzSan Lorenzo del EscorialxHistoryy16th century. 0aHistoric buildingszSpainzSan Lorenzo del Escorial. 0aMonasterieszSpainzSan Lorenzo del EscorialxHistoryy16th century. 0aPalaceszSpainzSan Lorenzo del EscorialxHistoryy16th century. 0aPower (Social sciences)zSpainzSan Lorenzo del EscorialxHistoryy16th century. 0aRenaissancezSpainzSan Lorenzo del Escorial. 7aHISTORY / Renaissance.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030016244840uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030016825940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300168259423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300168259/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY